main event: On September 6, 1952, in Middletown, Pa., two unidentified flying objects were observed for 5 minutes. A report with photographs was made about the sighting, and it was concluded that the objects were probably conventional aviation or possibly a meteor. There were also mentions of possible radar involvement.
interesting points: The observation lasted for 5 minutes, providing a substantial amount of time to study the objects.
There were photographs taken as evidence of the sighting.
The report mentioned the possibility of radar involvement, indicating potential corroborating evidence.
The objects were described as traveling from southeast to northwest at a high rate of speed with no sound, and they appeared to go below hills to the west of the field across the Susquehanna River.
Reliable observers, including at least two case guards, witnessed the event.
witnesses: reliable observers including at least two case guards
